
Why Python is failing where PHP succeeds — the technical explanation:
The issue isn't PHP version (5.6 vs 8.4). It's the process architecture of whatever PHP binary is running on your machine.
When PHP loads the OCI8 extension, it loads oci.dll from C:\instantclient_12_1. For that to work, the PHP process and oci.dll must be the same architecture — both 32-bit or both 64-bit. This is a fundamental rule of Windows DLL loading; it's not a Python rule or a PHP rule. It's an operating system rule.
Your C:\instantclient_12_1\oci.dll is 32-bit (file size 641 KB; 64-bit version is typically 2+ MB). So whichever PHP loads it successfully — 5.6 or 8.4 — that PHP process is also 32-bit.
Your Python in C:\ml_env_311 is 64-bit. A 64-bit process cannot load a 32-bit DLL. The OS prevents it at the kernel level. This is the DPI-1047 error.
