That's a real lockdown. Let me think through what's still possible.
Option 1 — Get a 64-bit Instant Client onto the machine via your PHP team.
The 64-bit Instant Client zip is an Oracle download, but it doesn't need to be installed. It's just files in a folder. If your PHP team or any colleague has internet access on another machine:
Have them download instantclient-basiclite-windows.x64-21.x.zip (~50 MB) from oracle.com/database/technologies/instant-client/winx64-64-downloads.html.
Copy the zip to a USB drive or send via internal network share.
Unzip to C:\instantclient_21_x_64 on your dev server.
Update app/dao/oracle.py to point at that folder.
You're not installing anything — just unzipping a folder you already have permission to write to (C: writable for your user is normal). This is not the same as software installation. Software installation requires admin to write to Program Files, modify registry, install services. Unzipping a folder requires nothing.
If your IT department considers "unzipping a Oracle-provided zip file" as software installation, then strictly speaking, you'd need to ask them. But functionally, this is the cleanest solution.
Option 2 — Have PHP do the Oracle queries on Python's behalf.
Your PHP works. So do this:
Write a small PHP script that:
Receives a request (e.g., via a simple PHP file served by your Apache).
Takes an item ID or item name as parameter.
Runs the Oracle query.
Returns JSON.
From Python, call this PHP endpoint via requests.get(). Python doesn't need Oracle at all — it just makes HTTP calls to your PHP server, which talks to Oracle.
This is the PHP-proxy approach I mentioned earlier as Option C. It's ugly but functionally complete.





